		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id71f7af5682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>6:5.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Law—Foreign</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287017101" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST9-11-43" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Iced76c0074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 9-11-43(c)</cite.query> equalizes the law of a foreign country and the law of another state and makes their consideration a matter of law rather than one of judicial notice. <eos/>
						<bos/>Prior to the enactment of this statute, Georgia law on judicially noticing the law of another state was confusing.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I784264c074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287017101" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST9-11-43" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Iced87d7074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 9-11-43(c)</cite.query> provides:</paratext>
					<display.quote>
						<para>
							<paratext>
								<begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>Determination of the law of other jurisdictions. <eos/>
								<bos/>A party who intends to raise an issue concerning the law of another state or of a foreign country shall give notice in his pleadings or other reasonable written notice. <eos/>
								<bos/>The court, in determining such law, may consider any relevant material or source, including testimony, whether or not submitted by a party or admissible under the rules of evidence. <eos/>
								<bos/>The court&apos;s determination shall be treated as a ruling on a question of law.<eos/>
								<bos/>
								<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I78428bd074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
						</para>
					</display.quote>
					<paratext>
						<?page no="162"?>Notice of intent to rely on foreign law is required before a party can establish such law in accordance with any of the three statutory methods or place a duty on the trial court to recognize judicially foreign law as published by authority.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78428bd174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] If a party does not give the required notice of his intention to use foreign law, then the court will apply Georgia law.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78428bd274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Under this Code section, the Georgia Court of Appeals has judicially noticed the law of another state in several cases.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78428bd374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] However, other cases have applied <cite.query w-src-number="0287017101" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST9-11-43" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Icedb3c9074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 9-11-43(c)</cite.query> and held that under the Civil Practice Act it was not necessary to plead the law of the other state.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78428bd474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] Under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017101" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-2-201" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Icedc751074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-2-201</cite.query>, a trial court must take judicial notice of a judicial opinion from a foreign jurisdiction if <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“published by authority … without the introduction of proof”<end.quote refid="QT_0002"/> so long as a party gives notice of its intent to rely upon the foreign law.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7842b2e074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>] Therefore, slip opinions of a foreign state, not yet published by authority, are not binding on a Georgia court.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7842b2e174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
		<footnote.block>
			<footnote ID="I784264c074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>1</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>Agnor, Judicial Notice of the Law of Another State, 12 Ga. Bar J. 379 (1950).<eos/>
							<bos/> See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017101" w-serial-number="0280312827" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="TS" w-pub-number="0134642" ID="Iced8566074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">McCormick on Evidence § 335 (6th ed.)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I78428bd074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>2</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>Notice of intent to rely on foreign law is required before a party can establish such law in accordance with any of the three statutory methods or place duty on the trial court to judicially recognize foreign law as published by authority. <eos/>
							<bos/>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017101" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST9-10-94" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Iced940c074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 9-10-94</cite.query> perforce provides requisite notice of intent to prove foreign law, as pertains to the issue of by whom service of process can be made thereunder. <eos/>
							<bos/>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017101" w-serial-number="1994168328" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Iced940c374d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Samay v. Som, 213 Ga. App. 812, 446 S.E.2d 230 (1994)</cite.query>
							<?page no="162"?>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I78428bd174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>3</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
